{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_queenofspades_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608737/1958031901/0361.xml":{"full_text":"-DAVID LAWRENCE\nUnemployment and the Slump\nU. Figures Cited to Show Joblessness\nIs Localized and Not Hitting All Cities\nLatest figure* from the\nU. S. Department of Labor\nahow that this Isn\u2019t a na\ntional recession, but that It is\na local recession. For the vast\nmajority of the labor areas of\nthe country are operating\nt under normal conditions and\n4 reveal relatively little un\nemployment.\nThus, for example, 149\nmajor areas are surveyed\nevery second month by the\nDepartment of Labor, and of\nthese 45 now are listed as\nhaving unemployment of 6\nper cent or more. A year ago\ni there were 19 areas in that\ncategory.\nIn addition, there are 89\nsmaller areas at present'With\n6 per cent or more unem\n-3 ployed, as contrasted with 57\nof the same type a year ago.\nWhat this means is that\n1 substantial unemployment\ncan be localized on the map.\nIt is not Nation-wide in the\nsense that it is affecting\nevery city and town in the\ncountry. It is prevalent only\nIn specific sections and par\nticular industries\n4 While there are one or more\nunemployment areas in 27\ndifferent States, this is a nor\nmal situation in the sense\nthat, with rare exceptions,\nsince the close of World War\nn unemployment areas have\ni dotted the Nation every year,\neven when business and em\nployment in other parts of\nr the country have been de\nscribed as booming and un\nemployment has been at a\nminimum.\nIt is this spotty condition\nwhich requires attention, and\nIt will not be cured by reme\ndies that propose to give\nextra money through tax\nreductions to persons who\nreally don\u2019t need it. A case\n-for comprehensive tax reduc\ntion\u2014bringing down the rates\nv. for corporations as well as\nfor individuals\u2014can be made\non the ground that receipts\nwould be increased if tax\nrates become productive and\nstimulating. But the type of\nWILLIAM Me C. MARTlN\u2014Substituting for Stokes\nThe Slump and Federal Spending\nReduced Prices to Increase Public Buying\nAnd Production Called Recovery Route\nBy WILLIAM McCHESNEY\nMARTIN, Jr.\nChairman. Board at Governor*.\nFederal Reserve Sr stem\nWhat Is troubling our econ\nomy now is some after-effects\nof inflation.\nIt Is highly regrettable that\nwe should have been brought\nto this pass, but it would be\nfruitless at this point to be\nlabor the subject of what we\nmight have done in the past\nto better the present.\nThe important,thing now is\nto deal sanely with today\u2019s\nproblems today and to re\nmember firmly that when the\nnext economic turn comes, as\nassuredly it will, the best way\nto fight deflation is to fight the\nInflation that leads to it.\nIn coping with today's prob\nlems. it is essential that we\nrecognize that prosperity is not\nbrought about merely by more\nand more spending. Prosperity\ncan come only from more effi\ncient production and distribu\ntion of goods and services at\nprices that people are able\nand willing to pay.\nv Vital as it is to achieve\nrecovery, it is even more vital\nto insure that it will be a\nrecovery that lasts\u2014a recov\nery that does not merely pro\nvide jobs, but lasting jobs.\nHence, the task before us is\nnot that of finding artificial\nstimulants that will bring\nprosperity for one day and a\ncollapse the next, but a task\nof laying the basis for a\nsound prosperity that will\nendure.\nThe Federal Reserve Sys\n-4 tem is bending its efforts to\nday to fostering credit con\nditions that will contribute to\nrecovery and the maximum\nsustainable growth of our\neconomy, as it was earlier\nwhen it was endeavoring to\ncombat the inflationary foun\ntainhead of today\u2019s troubles.\nIn recent months, the Fed\neral Reserve, using every one\nof the powers it possesses\u2014\nover discount rates, reserve\nrequirements, margin require-\nDORIS FLEESON\nWilliams and the Democrats\nMichigan Governor's Presidential Hopes\nSeen Depending on Unity of Factions\nDETROIT, Mich. The\npresidential prospects of Oov.\nO. Mennen Williams depend\non thrf possibility that grow*\nlng Democratic strength In\nthe West and Midwest can\nand will coalesce with the\nparty\u2019s liberal organizations\nof the industrial States and\nthe North.\nThe Michigan Governor Is\none of the most successful\npoliticians In the country. He\nIs seen as the certain winner\nof a sixth term this fall and\nhe has led In establishment\nof firm Democratic control of\nthis Important State which\nfor many years was stamped\nnormally Republican.\nHe Is, however, anathema\nto the powerful Southern\nminority of his party which\ncannot now name a candi\ndate for President but seelcs\nto exercise a veto power over\nanyone to whom it strongly\nobjects. It objects to Oov.\nWilliams because he helped\ntax reduction which merely is\ntemporary and, for example,\nforgives withholding taxes\nfor a few weeks, isn\u2019t going to\ncure the recession. It might\nmake matters worse.\nIt is significant that the\nDepartment of Labor surveys\non unemployment reveal the\nheaviest layoffs to be in\ntextiles, machinery and ma\nchine tools, metal-fabricating\nplants, automobile and parts\nmanufacturing, altcraft, rail\nroad equipment, and many\nrelated industries.\nNot enough attention has\nbeen focused on the fact that\nheavy-goods industries have\nbeen slowed down because\nAmerica's expansion pro\ngrams have been halted. It\nis estimated that there may\nbe $lO billion of private\nspending involved in the\nplans for heavy-goods expan\nsion which were laid aside in\nthe last two years due to\ncredit restraints. The need\nfor those projects still re\nmains. Now, with money\nrates eased, the next several\nmonths should see a revival\nin the manufacturing of\nheavy goods.\nIt has been argued that\nthe automobile industry is the\nkey to the present recession\nand that, once automobile\nbuying is stimulated, there\nwill be a revival in steel, coal,\nrailroad freight and a variety\nof industries now adversely\naffected. But it is interest\ning to note that preliminary\nsurveys show that people plan\nto buy a record number of\nused cars in 1958. This might\nIndicate that the prices of the\nnew cars are just high enough\nto cause hesitation by many\nwould-be buyers who are con\ntent for the present with\nused cars.\nA reduction of the excise\ntaxes on autos is being advo\ncated as one way to bring\nauto prices down. This un\ndoubtedly would stimulate\nsome sales, but it would do\nlittle good if the automobile\n(EDITOR\u2019S NOTE: This is\nanother in the \u201cStatesmen\u2019s\nSeries\u2019\u2019 by distinguished per\nsonages in Government, busi\nness, national affairs and the\nmilitary who are writing guest\ncolumns for Thomas L.\nStokes, who is seriously UU\n~~v\u2014\nments and open market oper\nations\u2014has operated to make\ncredit more available and\nthus cheaper.\nIn the credit and capital\nmarkets. Federal Reserve ac\ntions have contributed to a\nmarked easing that is illus\ntrated jpost dramatically by\nthe very sharp drop in mar\nket rates of interest\u2014the\nsharpest drop for any com\nparable period of which I\nhave knowledge.\nThis adjustment in credit\nand capital markets is help\ning to facilitate and cushion\nother adjustments in the\neconomy, as well as to\nstrengthen demands in im\nportant areas dependent on\ncredit financing. It is thus\nhelping to set the stage for\nrecovery in activity and em\nployment as soon as other\ndevelopments contribute to\nrevival.\nMonetary policy by itself,\nhowever, cannot assure re\nsumption of high-level em\nployment and sustainable\neconomic growth, although\nready availability of credit at\nreasonable cost is an essential\ningredient for recovery. It\nis incumbent upon business\nenterprises, financial institu\ntions, and labor organiza\ntions, as well as Government\ngenerally, to adjust policies\nand programs to foster re\ncovery.\nWe have been concerned,\nfor example, at the decline\nin output and employment\nwhile prices generally have\nbeen maintained and some\nprices even have risen fur\nther. Currently, it may\nbe noted, consumer prices\nto lead the loyalty oath\nstruggle In the 1952 conven\ntion and because it disliked\nhis close association with\nWalter Reuther, controversial\nhead of the automobile\nworkers union.\nThe South's able politi\ncians perhaps also sense In\nhim a quality of ruthlessness\nakin to their own. He at\ntacked the 1956 campaign of\nAdlai Stevenson as fatally\nmoderate and early predicted\nMr. Stevenson\u2019s defeat. Gov.\nWilliams would give the 1960\ncampaign a civil rights Issue\nwith the bark off.\nHis candidacy will offer the\nparty a test of Its professedly\nliberal principles in away\nthat the essential moderation\nof Mr. Stevenson as a per\nson and the compromises of\nsome of its leaders twice\nmanaged to evade.\nHe has come a long way\nfrom the sophomorlc loyalty\noath operation of 1952. In\nfact, his preconvention strat-\nworkers union were to threat\nen a strike this spring and\nforce into effect a higher\nwage scale which would kill\nmuch of the advantage\ngained by the reduction of\nexcise taxes. For it wouldn\u2019t\nhelp matters any if the auto\nmanufacturers had to raise\ntheir prices to offset wage\nIncreases. The automobile\ncompanies have said they\nwould pass on to the con\nsumer any' drop in excise\ntaxes, but they must Include\nin their prices any substan\ntial increase in wage costs.\nIf ever there was a time for\nstatesmanship in the labor\nunions, it is today when\nAmerica has been struggling\nto absorb its highest price\nlevels in history.\nThe cure for the recession\ndoes not lie in a general in\ncrease in purchasing power,\nwhich is bound to be small so\nfar as the individual is con\ncerned. but in helping the\nparticular Industries which\nnow are suffering severely\nfrom unemployment. Legis\nlators on Capitol Hill are\ntalking about antirecession\nmeasures that could conceiv\nably result in higher rather\nthan lower prices of goods\nand actually diminish pur\nchasing power. While tem\nporarily Improving matters,\nthese measures might bring\nwithin a few months the\nworst smash the American\neconomy has ever experi\nenced.\nCaution in applying reme\ndies for unemployment is\nmore important right now\nthan succumbing to panicky\ndemands for broad reduc\ntions in taxes to millions of\nindividuals who really do not\nneed them. Savings have\nrisen to new highs. There is\nno dearth of total purchasing\npower. There is, of course, a\nnoticeable fear and hesita\ntion due to what is happen\ning in a small number of la\nbor areas. Once there are\nmeasures taken, however, to\ncure the illness of the heavy\ngoods Industries, the national\neconomy will again be on an\neven keel.\n(Reproduction Rlchta Reserved)\nreached a new high in\nJanuary.\nHow soon recession is\nchecked and recovery is\nresumed will be Influenced\nby the rapidity with which\neconomic corrections and\nadaptations are made in\nfactors beyond the province\nof Federal Reserve policy\u2014\nthat is to say. in business\npricing policies, selling prac\ntices and productive effi\nciency; in wiage bargaming;\nin various financing arrange\nments, and in the incen\ntives to consumers to buy.\nIn the past, Uriee reduc\ntions during periods of con\ntraction served to stimulate\nincreased buying and output\nand thus to contribute to\ngeneral recovery and expan\nsion. Undoubtedly, lower\nprices now would prove to\nhave expansive benefits for\neconomic activity generally.\nWe all share the hope that\nthe recession will be moder\nate and short-lived, but it is\nnot possible to be completely\ncertain about the future\ncourse of economic activity.\nThere is a range of views\ncurrently held regarding the\nduration and extent of this\nrecession, and of the timing\nand vigor of the ensuing re\ncovery.\nIn my own view the under\nlying strengths of the econ\nomy are many. The infla\ntionary trends seem to have\nhalted before creating mal\nadjustments of such severity\nas to lead to a protracted\nperiod of liquidation and\nstructural realignmentin\nthe economy. If needed re\nadjustments are promptly\nmade, the current recession\nmay be moderate and short\nlived, and healthy revival\nshould set in, progressing to\nnew records of economic per\nformance and new high levels\nof national well-being.\nBut let us not be misled\ninto vain hope this will come\nabout without effort on the\npart of all of us, for much\ndepends upon the speed with\nwhich needed readjustments\nare made.\niConrrliht. 185*. br\nUnited FMturu Syndicate. Inc.)\negy is strongly reminiscent\nof the manner In which\nThomas E. Dewey, that\nnever-wlldly-popular Repub\nlican. managed to get two\npresidential nominations.\nIn his State chairman, Neil\nStabler, Oov. Williams has\na quiet and adept organizer.\nMr. Stabler has kept out\nof the limelight and has\nstifled all attempts to put\nhim forward as national\nchairman. Instead, he has\nbeen serving as chairman of\nan advisory committee on\nparty organization in the 48\nStates.\nOutside the South, those\nsame delegations also are\nscudded with trained labor\npoliticians. Prom such men\nGov. Williams will not get\nthe worst of it.\nThe effort to make Oov.\nWilliams\u2019 abilities better\nknown is already under way\nThe current Harvard Busi\nness Review has an article in\nwhich he answers a persua\nsive yes to the question,\n\u201cCan businessmen be Demo\ncrats?\u201d\nLOUIE ~*y Horry Haiton\nPOTOMAC FEVER\nFLETCHER KNCBCL\nIke implores Republicans to have confidence in a return\nof prosperity. This will be known as his \u201cdouble-chins up\u2019\u2019\nspeech.\n\nCape Canaveral, Florida, is the ideal spot for a Russian-\nUnited States summit conference. Ample facilities for liquid\nfueling, propaganda count-downs\u2014and blast-offs.\n\nOne Democratic candidate charges the Eisenhower team\nwith two recessions. One is the slump in business. The other\nis the sudden collapse of Democratic preoccupation with\nouter space. 7\n\nAttorney General Rogers says the Republican future is\n\u201cvery bright.\u2019\u2019 In fact, in November the explosion may be so\nterrific, the sky will be aglow for miles around.\n\nThe 1 logic of the human male is formidable. He is the\nonly animal that can deplore the vanity of the female while\ngazing admiringly at his own reflection in a mirror over a\npublic bar.\n\nSatellite Sports News: The Nsvy will open its outer space\nmajor league season late this spring\u2014after an extended tour\non the grapefruit circuit.\nSTOP THE STAMP TAX!\nDEFEAT THE 5\u2019 STAMP!\nV _\nT \\g\\ tfWLf- to\u2019\nP f-o u M v\"*,t\nA petition to Cpngress from a national organization 700,000 a year for postage, 90% \u00bbof it first f\nof business firms, retailers, banks insurance class. The nickel stamp \u2018WO'qld increase New\ncompanies, philanthropic organizations, and York\u2019s postage bill by some $1,000*000! New\nproducers of printing and direct mail: York citizens would have to make it up in\nWhile leaders in Congress and the Ad- taxes.\nministration are seriously considering a tax _.\ncut, Postmaster General Summerfield is push- S ml,ar u ezes ocal government\ning his plan to levy a $500,000,000 tax on first- J lud Be\u2018s8 e \u2018f ould take p aca a ac ss thc co\nciass mail users with new, higher rates. Does l n ia a ar or\nthis make sense? S f s i 7W99\nFlorida $850,000, Wisconsin $676,505, Oregon\nTax-cut discussions are based on the need $590,000, and so on. For New York City the\nto put more money in the hands of consumers, annual postage bill is $92 1.615, for Chicago\ninvestors, and employers. Doesn\u2019t a boost $320,000, Philadelphia $307,170, Pittsburgh\nin postage charges (from 3c to sc) fly in the $148,205, Boston $143,318, etc.\nface of this need? We think so, and we hope\nCongress agrees. Mr. Summerfield\u2019s 5c stamp is nothing\nPostage costs run into thousands of dol- less than a tax. This is because first class\nlars monthly for countless business firms. mail under his proposal would produce rev-\nMany small firms must rely on the mails as a enue equal to 140% of its allocated costs. The\nsubstitute for manpower in competition with extra 40% is a stamp tax\u2014the kind of tax our\nbig business. This is a poor time for the Gov- colonist forefathers got very angry about\nernment to inflate their costs. One unwanted some 200 years ago!\nresult would be a loss in tax revenue as higher\ncosts cut into business profits. That\u2019s a \u201ctax Latest available figures show that first\ncut,\u201d all right, but without benefit to the tax- class letter mail produces a $2,800,000 excess\npayer. \u00b0f revenue over expenditures under the pres\nxt ivr j ent 3c rate. Yet Mr. Summerfield wants to\nMembership of the National Federat.cn raisc thj rate by for non local mai and\nof Independent Business, Inc., a leading small y for loca mai i (Inddentall he himwlf\nbusiness organisation, recently voted their testified before a Congressional committee\nopposition to Mr Summerfield s nickel stamp e\u00dfs than two that \u201canv rate differ\nproposal. Officials of a Retail Wholesale and enttal between local and non-local first-class\nDepartment Store Union District recently fetter mail would be discriminatory, costly,\ntold their Congressmen the rate boosts in and ext dilflcutt to administer.\nfiyt and third class mail would throw a Public confus f on wouM w j despr ead\u201d)\nthird of their members out of work. r\nStates and municipalities, already hard- While the rest of the country talks about\npressed financially, would also suffer. For reducing taxes, Mr. Summerfield talks about\nexample, the State of New York spends sl,- raising them!\ni\nWE URGE CONGRESS:\nSTOP THE STAMP TAX! DEFEAT THE 5' STAMP!\nThe Association of First Class Mailers\n352 Fourth Ave., New York 10, N. Y.\nWashington Office: 211 Wyatt Bldg., DI. 7-4514\nCONSTANTINE BROWN\nIsrael and Non-Expansionism\nLeaders Assert Agcricultural Science\nMakes New Territory Unnecessary\nTEL AVIV, Israel (By Air\nmail) \u2014When I pointed out\nto Israeli officials and others\nthat the aggressive attitude\nof the Arabs is based on what\nthey feel is their need for\nself-defense against Israeli\nexpansionist ideas to make\nroom for thousands of Jews\nfrom North Africa and other\nareas, the response was that\nsuch a policy has been given\nup\u2014if it ever existed.\nThere may be hundreds of\nthousands of Jews behind\nthe Iron Curtain and in\nMorocco, Algeria (if the\nFrench withdraw) and Tu\nnisia who hanker for the\nnew promised land. But there\ncan be room for all the im\nmigrants as well as the nat\nural growth of population.\nIt is true that Israel has\nonly 8,000 square miles. The\nNegeb desert represents 55\nper cent of the area. But\nthere are close to two mil\nlion people living here in rel\native, comfort. Every inch of\ntillable land is scientifically\ndeveloped and new industries\ncapable of providing an eco\nnomic living for this country\nspring up every day, thanks\nto the influx of capital from\nthe West (especially from the\nUnited States).\nTechnical know-how exists\nhere in a greater compara\ntive measure than in the\nWest. There are thousands\nof skilled engineers, chemists,\netc., who could have won\nfame and fortune in Amer\nica or Britain. But they pre\nfer to offer their talents to\nbuild up this new Jewish re\npublic. There is no reason to\nbelieve, this reporter was\ntold, that minds which helped\nsmash the atom and contrib\nTHE EVENING STAR, Washington. D. C.\nWEDNESDAY. MARCH t\u00bb. ISftS\nuted to the creation of guided\nmissiles and earth satellites\ncannot solve the problem of\ntaking the salt out of sea\nwater to be used for irriga\ntion.\nWhen irrigation comes, 55\nper cent of the present Is\nraeli territory, the Negeb\ndesert, will become another\nGarden of Eden where at\nleast another two million peo\nple could be settled. Scien\ntists already are busy seeking\nways to desalt the waters\nof the Red Sea for irrigation.\nThis is expected to be ready\nwithin the next five years.\nWith desert irrigation, the\nIsraelis feel there is no rea\nson why their country should\nnot become economically the\n\u201cSwitzerland of the Middle\nEast\"\u2014the most advanced\nagricultural and economic\nstate between the Mediter\nranean and the Pacific. This\nmay be overoptimism and\npardonable pride. But there\nis no doubt that progress\nin industrial and agricultural\nfields here in recent years is\nspectacular not only by East\nern but by Western standards.\nTTiere is no doubt that\nthere was thought of expan\nsion in the past. But after\nthe victory against the\nEgyptians in 1956 and the\ndefeat at the hands of the\nUnited Nations forced them\nto get back to their borders,\nthe Israelis seem to have\ndropped the chip from their\nshoulder. They have become\nmore realistic politically when\nthey discovered that the In\nternational Zionists and espe\ncially the Zionists in the\nUnited States have either\nlost some of their political\npower-or do not want to use\nit any longer on behalf of\ntheir brethren here.\nThis reporter is not in a\nposition to know whether the\nJerusalem government may\nstill harbor unrealistic dreams\nof expansion. But he is con\nvinced that the military and\nthe others who are directly\nresponsible for this country\u2019s\nsecurity do not want more\nterritory containing Arabs. As\nit is, these men feel that the\n160,000 Arabs (inclusive of\nsome 35,000 Christian Arabs\nand about 15,000 Druses) con\nstitute a security threat to\nthe country. It is this group\nwhich lives in its own areas\nthat vote so consistently\nCommunist that they now\nsend six Communist repre\nsentatives to the Knesset\n(Israeli Parliament). Os\nthese, three claim to be pure\nMarxist doctrinaires and only\nthe balance is still loyal to\nRussia\u2019s \u201canti-imperialist\npolicies.\u201d\nThe Mbslem Arabs are not\nallowed to serve in the armed\nforces. The Christian Arabs\ncan volunteer, as can the\nDruses. But despite the ap\nparent resignation of all of\nthem to accept the state of\nIsrael where they live, there\nis no doubt where their al\nlegiance would be in the\nevent of war between Israel\nand its neighbors.\nRealistic leaders here say\nit would not serve their pur\npose to try to expand at the\nexpense of their neighbors\nwhen such an expansion is\ncertain to produce only new\nheadaches for a country\nwhich has more than its\nshare.\nAnd this reporter has\nfound nobody inside or out\nside the government who\nwould be willing to solve the\nquestion of the 750,000 Arab\nrefugees from Israel by per\nmitting them to return here.\nA-21","height":"28792","width":"18294"}}
